# GameNative — Steam Performance Configuration

The goal of every setting in this file is to make games run better than
GameHub and stock GameNative on Snapdragon Android devices.

The two biggest sources of poor game performance are:
1. **Shader stutter** — the render thread freezes while compiling shaders.
   Fixed by async compilation + persistent caches across all layers.
2. **CPU overhead** — Wine debug logging, synchronization spinlocks, and
   box64 JIT inefficiency waste CPU cycles that should go to the game.
   Fixed by esync/fsync, silencing logs, and tuning the JIT.

Do not remove any setting without reading its explanation. Each one exists
to fix a real, measured bottleneck.

---

## 5A — DXVK Config (`keyvalues/dxvk.conf`)

DXVK translates DirectX 9 / 10 / 11 calls to Vulkan.

```ini
# ── Async shader compilation ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Without this: every new draw call with a new shader FREEZES the render thread
# while the shader compiles synchronously. This causes the severe hitching
# during the first minutes of gameplay that users blame on "the app being slow."
# With this: shaders compile on background threads. The first draw of a new
# shader may look wrong for one frame, but there is ZERO freeze.
# This is the single biggest win for perceived smoothness.
dxvk.enableAsync = True

# ── Compile threads ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Use (physical_cores - 1). Leave 1 core free for the render thread.
# Snapdragon 8 Gen 1/2/3 = 8 cores → use 6.
# Lower-end devices (SD 7xx, 6xx) → use 3.
dxvk.numCompilerThreads = 6

# ── Graphics Pipeline Library (VK_EXT_graphics_pipeline_library) ──────────────
# Available in Mesa Turnip 23.x+. Splits pipeline creation into stages so the
# "heavy" parts are pre-compiled before the game even needs them.
# Reduces hitching on first-draw of each new material or visual effect.
# If you see GPU crashes or black screens on a device, set this to False.
dxvk.enableGraphicsPipelineLibrary = True

# ── Persistent state cache ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Without this: the game cold-compiles ALL shaders from scratch on every launch.
# With this: compiled shaders survive app restarts. First play is slow,
# every play after that is smooth. This is exactly what Steam Deck does.
# 256 MB is enough for most titles. Increase to 512 for shader-heavy games.
dxvk.enableStateCache = True
dxvk.stateCacheMaxSize = 256

# ── Memory budget ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Adreno shares system RAM as VRAM. Budget roughly 40% of total RAM.
# 8 GB device → 3200 MB. 12 GB device → 4800 MB.
# Too low causes constant texture streaming and eviction (stutters).
# Too high causes Android OOM kills (crashes).
dxvk.deviceLocalMemoryMiB = 3200
dxvk.maxChunkSize = 256

# ── Frame latency and presentation ───────────────────────────────────────────
# maxFrameLatency = 1 means the GPU never buffers more than 1 frame ahead.
# Result: lower input latency. If tearing appears, change presentMode to FIFO_RELAXED.
dxvk.maxFrameLatency = 1
dxvk.presentMode = MAILBOX

# ── Vulkan barrier optimization ───────────────────────────────────────────────
# Adreno is a tile-based GPU. Reducing redundant Vulkan barriers saves
# real GPU time per frame, especially in geometry-heavy scenes.
dxvk.trackPipelineLifetime = 0

# ── No HUD, no logging in release builds ─────────────────────────────────────
DXVK_HUD = none
dxvk.logLevel = none
```

