## 5H — Box64 Tuning

Box64 translates x86_64 game binaries to ARM64 via a JIT compiler ("Dynarec").
Most Steam games running on GameNative go through Box64. These variables
improve JIT throughput and correctness:

```bash
# ── Dynarec: larger translation blocks ───────────────────────────────────────
# Translates bigger x86 chunks at once → fewer JIT recompile interrupts per second.
export BOX64_DYNAREC_BIGBLOCK=1

# ── Strong memory ordering ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# x86 has stricter memory ordering than ARM. Without this, some games crash or
# produce wrong results due to race conditions in translated multi-threaded code.
export BOX64_DYNAREC_STRONGMEM=1

# ── x87 double precision ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Some games depend on x87 80-bit float precision for physics calculations.
# Without this, floating point results differ between x86 and the Box64 translation,
# causing physics glitches or incorrect game logic.
export BOX64_DYNAREC_X87DOUBLE=1

# ── Fast float rounding ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Small CPU win. Uses ARM native float rounding instead of emulating x86 modes.
export BOX64_DYNAREC_FASTROUND=1

# ── Silent logging ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Box64 log output is expensive. 0 = completely silent. Never set above 0 in release.
export BOX64_LOG=0

# ── RAM-backed temp dir for JIT code cache ───────────────────────────────────
# Box64 writes compiled ARM64 blobs here. tmpfs (RAM-backed) avoids flash I/O latency.
export BOX64_TEMPDIR=/tmp/box64cache
```

